✅ Solution: Inject CosmosDBConfig in a Simplified Manner

You’re right! The previous version does not use CosmosDBConfig, which means we can’t dynamically fetch CosmosDB credentials (like endpoint, key, database, and container names).

To fix this, we can inject CosmosDBConfig using constructor-based dependency injection while keeping the implementation simple and efficient.

🚀 Updated CosmosDBRepository.java (with CosmosDBConfig)

import com.azure.cosmos.*;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;

import javax.annotation.PreDestroy;

/**
 * Cosmos DB Repository for Read-Only Queries.
 * <p>
 * - Uses a **single shared connection** across all API calls.
 * - Injects **CosmosDBConfig** to dynamically get configuration.
 * - Initializes **once** and remains open until application shutdown.
 * - Uses **Gateway Mode** (best for read-heavy workloads).
 * </p>
 */
@Repository
public class CosmosDBRepository {

    /** Logger for debugging connection status */
    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CosmosDBRepository.class);

    /** Shared Cosmos Client instance */
    private final CosmosClient cosmosClient;

    /** Cosmos database and container */
    private final CosmosDatabase cosmosDatabase;
    private final CosmosContainer cosmosContainer;

    /**
     * Constructor-based Dependency Injection.
     * Initializes the Cosmos DB connection ONCE at startup.
     *
     * @param cosmosDBConfig Injected configuration for Cosmos DB.
     */
    public CosmosDBRepository(CosmosDBConfig cosmosDBConfig) {
        try {
            logger.info("🔄 Initializing Cosmos DB connection...");

            // Build Cosmos Client using configuration values
            this.cosmosClient = new CosmosClientBuilder()
                    .endpoint(cosmosDBConfig.getEndpoint())
                    .key(cosmosDBConfig.getKey())
                    .gatewayMode() // Optimized for read-heavy workloads
                    .consistencyLevel(ConsistencyLevel.SESSION) // Balanced consistency level
                    .buildClient();

            // Get database and container from config
            this.cosmosDatabase = cosmosClient.getDatabase(cosmosDBConfig.getDatabase());
            this.cosmosContainer = cosmosDatabase.getContainer(cosmosDBConfig.getContainer());

            logger.info("✅ Cosmos DB connection established successfully.");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("❌ Failed to initialize Cosmos DB client: ", e);
            throw new RuntimeException("Error initializing Cosmos DB", e);
        }
    }

    /**
     * Retrieves the shared Cosmos DB container instance.
     *
     * @return the active {@link CosmosContainer} instance.
     */
    public CosmosContainer getContainer() {
        return cosmosContainer;
    }

    /**
     * Closes the Cosmos DB connection when the application is shutting down.
     */
    @PreDestroy
    public void close() {
        if (cosmosClient != null) {
            cosmosClient.close();
            logger.info("✅ Cosmos DB connection closed.");
        }
    }
}

📌 Key Improvements

Feature	Why This Works Well?
✅ Uses CosmosDBConfig	Fetches values dynamically (no hardcoded values).
✅ Constructor-Based Injection	Ensures CosmosDBConfig is properly initialized by Spring.
✅ Singleton Cosmos Client	Only one CosmosClient instance is created (efficient).
✅ Connection Stays Open	Closes only when the application shuts down.
✅ Optimized for Queries	Uses gatewayMode() (better for read-heavy workloads).

🚀 Updated CosmosDBConfig.java

If you haven’t already defined CosmosDBConfig, here’s a simple way to do it:

import org.springframework.boot.context.properties.ConfigurationProperties;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import java.util.List;

/**
 * Configuration class for Azure Cosmos DB properties.
 */
@Configuration
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "azure.cosmos")
public class CosmosDBConfig {

    private String endpoint;
    private String key;
    private String database;
    private String container;
    private List<String> preferredRegions; // Optional for region-based optimizations

    // Getters & Setters
    public String getEndpoint() { return endpoint; }
    public void setEndpoint(String endpoint) { this.endpoint = endpoint; }

    public String getKey() { return key; }
    public void setKey(String key) { this.key = key; }

    public String getDatabase() { return database; }
    public void setDatabase(String database) { this.database = database; }

    public String getContainer() { return container; }
    public void setContainer(String container) { this.container = container; }

    public List<String> getPreferredRegions() { return preferredRegions; }
    public void setPreferredRegions(List<String> preferredRegions) { this.preferredRegions = preferredRegions; }
}

